post_text:
Do you know a student that could benefit from services offered through Project Help?

Project HELP is a program that identifies and supports students that are displaced and living with friends or relatives, or in a car, hotel, and/or public place.

Project Help offers the following services:
• classroom supplies
• school uniforms
• hygiene supplies
• tutoring
• referrals to community agencies
• educational support programming for families

Together, we can break down barriers to provide all students with a quality education.

Refer families to:
Vanessa Shaffer Coordinator of Project HELP vshaffer@starkvillesd.com Emerson Family School 1504 Louisville St. 662-324-2551

Click on the link for more information:
https://www.starkvillesd.com/departments/family-centered-programs/school-services

post_text: Our friends Theatre MSU are hosting a socially-distanced performance. Masks required.
shared_text:
Theatre MSU
September 1 at 2:02 PM ·

BIG ANNOUNCEMENT: Since we can't bring families to the theatre, we are bringing theatre to families.

Commedia Robin Hood will be performed on 3 dates in 3 locations!

Thursday, Sept 16th at 6pm at MSU amphitheatre
Saturday, Sept 19th at 2pm at JL King Park
Sunday, Sept 20th at 2pm at McKee Park

Please make sure you do the following
1. Go to events.msstate.edu to reserve your spots. Even if you choose free tickets, we need an accurate count so we stay within Covid guidelines
2. Bring a blanket (and some snacks) for your family. We will be outside on the grass so you'll want something to sit on.
3. Wear your mask! All of our actors will be showing off their cool masks. We want to see yours too!

post_text:
Excellent learning experiences extend beyond the walls of our classrooms.

Whether your child is learning at home or in the classroom, virtual learning will likely be a part of your child's educational experience for the 2020-21 school year.

The District's virtual learning model reflects our commitment to providing students with high-quality instructional experiences and to meeting the needs of students and their families.

Our virtual learning team is here to support students, teachers and families as we learn together.

Check out the District’s virtual learning guides for Elementary and Secondary students, how-to videos and more to get started planning for your family’s virtual learning experience.

https://www.starkvillesd.com/virtual

Enjoy the photos and join us Tuesday at 11 am via Facebook Live Starkville Oktibbeha Consolidated School District for our virtual ribbon cutting.
#ExpectExcellence

post_text: Covid-19 has challenged all of us in big and small ways, but there’s still excellence to experience! We’re so glad you could join us for today’s tour of Partnership Middle School and that you enjoyed your tour guide! We can’t wait to welcome our students and teachers back to school with confidence!
shared_text:

July 31 at 6:34 PM ·

So not only did we get to take our tour of the Partnership Middle School today, but we had the added pleasure of the tour being lead by Dr. Peasant. Can I just say how much it did my spirit good to be in his presence?! He cares so much about students and educators, and I’m super grateful for the hard work he and his staff has been putting in this since March to prepare for this year. An excellent partnership comes to fruition for the 2020-2021 school year! Starkville Oktibbeha Consolidated School District and Mississippi State University invite you to join us via Facebook Live as we celebrate the opening of Partnership Middle School with a Ribbon Cutting on Tuesday, August 4 at 11:00am.

With innovative teaching techniques, collaborative learning spaces, and the opportunity to develop research-based best practices in rural education, this groundbreaking partnership re-imagines middle school for 21st century students and educators. Visit the SOSD Facebook page to celebrate with us!

#ExpectExcellence #StarkvilleSpark #HailState

post_text:
The Starkville Oktibbeha School District has released its return to school guide, Staying Safe Together at the following link:
https://www.starkvillesd.com/covid19/news/1685075/staying-safe-together-return-to-school-guide-released

This guide details protocols for face coverings, hand-washing, social distancing, disinfecting and sanitization plan, transportation, health screenings, suspected or confirmed Covid-19 cases, and much more.

The guide is a starting point for a safe and healthy start to the 2020-21 school year.

District and school leaders are constantly monitoring the latest information available to the schools. As new information is received, the District's return to school guide will be updated accordingly.

One thing that will not change is our commitment to helping each student discover his or her passion, purpose & potential.

As #JacketFamily, we’ll get through this together.

The guide is a starting point for a safe and healthy start to the 2020-21 school year.

District and school leaders are constantly monitoring the latest information available to the schools. As new information is received, the District's return to school guide will be updated accordingly.

One thing that will not change is our commitment to helping each student discover his or her passion, purpose & potential.

As #JacketFamily, we’ll get through this together.

post_text: Don't miss this special virtual performance of the Starkville High School Theatre Cabaret!
shared_text:
YOUTUBE.COM
SHS Thespian Troupe 1180 Virtual Cabaret (Quabaret)

Starkville High School Theatre
May 12 at 2:06 AM ·

We were heart broken that we could not bring Young Frankenstein fully to life this Spring. However, some of our performers still want to share their art with you. They taught themselves these songs and had coaching from me only through video. This is all them, and I am as always amazed at their passion and their bravery to put themselves out there for this video. Please enjoy our Quarantine Cabaret (Quabaret). Also, at the end there is a tribute to our graduating class of 2020! 🧑🏻‍🎓
https://youtu.be/y-LyLmmfzc8

The Savages are #JacketFamily official with their first #JacketFamily photo!

Meet Dr. Savage, his wife Angela, and their children Amara, Amarion, and Amaya.

Amara will be a freshman at Mississippi State University in the fall. Amarion will be a 10th grader at Starkville High School. And Amaya will be a 6th grader at the SOCSD-MSU Partnership School.

Dr. Angela Savage is the Director of Field Education and instructor at Mississippi State University-Meridian campus in the College of Arts and Sciences Social Work Program.

Welcome Dr. Savage & family!

Our meals 2 go program which currently serves students on Mondays and Wednesdays and provides 8 meals each week will be closed May 25-29 during the week of Memorial Day to allow our cafeteria staff to plan and prepare for our summer meal program.

We will share information with parents about our summer learning options and our summer meal schedule when those plans are finalized.

Thank you in advance for your support and understanding as our school district continues to respond to Covid-19.

post_text:
Tomorrow is a big day for the #SHSClassof2020. Our SHS Valedictorian Kyran Williams-Roberts and Salutatorian Grant Peterson will lead the way as each member of the #SHSClassof2020 walks across the stage for their individual graduation ceremony.

Kyran will attend Duke University. He is an AP Scholar with Distinction, and he is a member of the SHS 30+ Club.

Grant will attend Mississippi State University. He is an AP Scholar with Honor, and he is a member of the SHS 30+ Club. Grant was also named SHS's STAR Student for his ACT score of 34.

Congratulations Kyran & Grant! We can't wait to celebrate your graduation with you and your classmates!

Got library books? Bring them back!

Our school libraries love sharing books with our students to read, and they love it when our students return those books to share with even more students.

All schools have drop boxes located in front of their school offices for students/parents to return books. The drop box at Overstreet Elementary School is located in the bottom drawer of the filing cabinet.

Thank you in advance for your efforts to support

Are you joining the #JacketFamily for the 2020-21 school year? Sudduth Elementary School is now accepting required documents for new student registration ONLY via email.

If your child will be a new student in kindergarten or first grade at Sudduth Elementary School for the 2020-21 school year, you can submit your child's required documents, including two proofs of residency, birth certificate and immunization record, via email to lwells@starkvillesd.com.

Parents of new students must also complete an online registration form. Proofs of residency must be current within 30 days, and all documents must be legible. For complete registration details, including a list of required documents and acceptable proofs of residency, click on the link below and register today!

https://www.starkvillesd.com/registration/index

What a fun way to celebrate excellence! Supt. Eddie Peasant congratulated our students who earned a score of 30+ on the ACT along with our inaugural class of seniors selected for the Early Honors College program at MSU during a drive thru celebration. During the drive thru, each student received an Excellence in the House yard sign because we want to share their achievement with our greater Starkville community and a pizza "to go" from Stromboli's since we were not able to gather together for our pizza lunch. Please share your congratulations with these outstanding students!

Photos Courtesy: Laura Daniels Photography

Some of our Sudduth Elementary students have new class pets... Caterpillars! Through art and science lessons, students are learning, observing, and documenting the life cycle of the caterpillars as they grow to become butterflies. So far, we’ve discovered that “they crawled” and “they have too many legs.” 😉 We’ll keep you posted on what happens next!

@StarkvilleSD and Starkville High School recognize 37 students who have earned a score of 30 of higher on the ACT!

Please join us as we celebrate and congratulate the following students for this outstanding achievement:

Rachel Adair, Jasmine Baker, Simon Banzhaf, AP Anshuman Behera, Peyton Brigham, Jaxon Brooks, John Geoffrey Campbell, Hannah Daniels, James Fairley, Jasper Gray, May Grace Holt, Andrew Keith, Katherine Leigh, Catherine Li, Caden Luke, Ningthou Lyem, Grace May, Caroline Nobles, Soyeon Park, Jack Perry, Grant Peterson, Keyan Rahimi, Angela Ross, Noah Scott, Dawson Smith, Cooper Snell, Makenzie Stone, Sarah Strickland, Qiancheng Sun, Mandy Sun, Matthew Swiderski, Andrew Walters, Kyron Williams-Roberts, Ella Wubben, Jessica Yan, Andrew Yu, and Amy Zhang

#ExpectExcellence

*We want to recognize every student who has earned a score of 30+ on the ACT! Students who earned a score of 30 or higher on the ACT and are not included on this list should email nthomas@starkvillesd.com.

Many of our Jacket traditions are taking a different form this year, and this will be an on-going opportunity for our #JacketFamily to meet the SHS Class of 2020, learn about their accomplishments and their future plans, and to share our blessings for them in the comment section.

We will eventually be sharing some of our Class of 2020 content on FB, but for now, we hope you’ll join us on Instagram or on the SOSD Twitter account, and let’s celebrate our seniors together!

Parents, we have made some adjustments to our free Meals 2 Go service. The District is no longer able to provide door-to-door meal delivery or facilitate volunteer meal delivery.

Meal service pick-ups at 7 community and 2 mobile sites will continue each week on Monday, Wednesday and Friday during Covid-19 school closure.

In addition, meal packs for children ages 0-18 are available for child pick-up, parent pick-up and volunteer pick-up. Please visit the following link for a list of sites, drive-up/walk-up times and more information about how meals may be picked up.

Jacket Family, please take note of the following important update about our Meal Delivery Service: Bus Delivery Suspended March 25; Drive-up/Walk-up Service Remains Open

As the Covid-19 outbreak expands across our state and community, we have made the difficult decision to suspend meal delivery service beginning Wednesday, March 25.

We WILL offer meal delivery service on Tuesday, March 24. Our drive-up/walk-up sites at Sudduth Elementary School and Henderson Ward Stewart Elementary School will remain open.

Parents of SHS Seniors:
We love all of you and your seniors! Like you, we are disappointed that some of our plans for celebrating the Class of 2020 may have to change, but rest assured, the #JacketFamily WILL celebrate you. We don’t know quite what that will look like yet, but we hope you’ll join us in 2 first steps:

1. We’d like EVERY SHS Senior to complete the Senior Information Form at www.starkvillesd.com/covid19/seniors
You’ll be able upload a senior photo if you have one and we encourage you to be thorough. Tell us everything! 🐝

2. We’ve created a new Instagram account devoted to celebrating the Class of 2020. We’d love for you to share it with your senior, your family and the community. Follow at www.instagram.com/jacketseniorclass 🐝

1. We’d like EVERY SHS Senior to complete the Senior Information Form at www.starkvillesd.com/covid19/seniors
You’ll be able upload a senior photo if you have one and we encourage you to be thorough. Tell us everything! 🐝

2. We’ve created a new Instagram account devoted to celebrating the Class of 2020. We’d love for you to share it with your senior, your family and the community. Follow at www.instagram.com/jacketseniorclass 🐝

Excellence delivers! The Starkville Oktibbeha School District will offer meal delivery service for our FREE Meals 2 Go program beginning today. Delivery will begin at 10:30 am and conclude around 12:30 pm. Buses will follow their normal routes. The District’s FREE Meals 2 Go is available to children 0-18. All children who would like to receive a meal must be present at the bus stop. Adult service will NOT be available through our bus delivery program. Please be patient as we begin this delivery service. Times should improve and become more consistent as the week progresses.

The District’s meal service will also be distributed from three school sites: Sudduth Elementary, Henderson Ward Stewart Elementary and Starkville High School from 10:30 am until 12:30 pm weekdays. Drive-up and walk-up service available at each school site in the bus lane located next to the cafeteria.

For complete details on our Meals to Go program, click on the link below:

https://www.starkvillesd.com/covid19/meal-services

SOSD will begin offering FREE Meals 2 Go to children 0-18 on Tues, March 17 at three school sites: Sudduth Elementary, HWS Elementary & SHS, 10:30am - 12:30pm weekdays. Drive-up and walk-up service available at each school site in the bus lane located next to cafeteria.

Children must be physically present to receive a meal. Adults who are chaperoning/transporting children to school sites may purchase a meal for $3.15 at school site. Cash only accepted.

Partners in Excellence! The Starkville-Oktibbeha School District-MSU Partnership School was honored by the Mississippi Association of Partners in Education (MAPE) in the university category of the program’s Partnership Excellence Awards. The 128,000-square-foot school on the MSU campus will serve every sixth and seventh grade student in the school district beginning this August. It also will serve as a demonstration site for preservice teachers in MSU’s College of Education, along with other collaborations that combine university and school district resources to enhance students’ education experiences.

post_text:
Excellence is GrOWing at The Partnership School!

The Starkville Oktibbeha School District was awarded a $900,000 grant from Blue Cross & Blue Shield of Mississippi to support the District’s overarching goal to create school environments that emphasize healthy living. The funds will be used to implement the Wellness Incentive for Starkville Partnerships (WISP) project, a comprehensive school health and wellness program, at the Partnership School.

The WISP initiative includes multiple school gardens & mobile kitchens to facilitate meaningful, hands-on experiences, including planting, harvesting, cooking and tasting opportunities. A GrOW (Gardening and Overall Wellness) classroom will introduce all sixth-graders to nutrition, gardening, wellness activities and healthy behaviors. Seventh-graders will have their own classroom “garden pod” that will be incorporated into academic subjects such as science, math and language arts. The initiative also includes plans for a greenhouse, school farmers’ market, family cooking nights and fitness classes.
#ExpectExcellence #StarkvilleSpark

SHS Class of 2021: Do you have an excellent academic record? Do you want to challenge yourself during your senior of high school?

Join us on Tuesday, Feb. 18, at 6 pm for an Early Honors Academy Interest Meeting at Griffis Hall on the campus of Mississippi State University.

Early Honors Academy is a semester-long program offered through a partnership with MSU’s Judy and Bobby Shackouls Honors College and the Starkville Oktibbeha School District.

Rising high school seniors are invited to apply based on their academic resume. Applicants will be interviewed and selected based on the strength of their composite credentials, including advanced placement coursework, using a rubric created through a collaboration between the Shackouls Honors College and SOCSD.

Learn more about the Academic Houses at Starkville High School at www.starkvillesd.com/academichouses.

Learn more about the Shackouls Honors College at www.honors.msstate.edu

"A big part of my great-grandfather's story was to never forget, to remember your history because it can repeat itself."
- Kate Dickerson, SHS Junior

Kate Dickerson remembers her great-grandfather, a prison of war, as she and SHS history teacher Craig Wood prepare to walk in the footsteps of history. The SHS student-teacher team is one of only 16 in the country selected for National History Day’s Sacrifice for Freedom®: World War II in the Pacific Student and Teacher Institute.

SHS student Kate Dickerson and SHS history teacher Craig Wood are one of only 16 student/teacher teams in the country selected for National History Day’s Sacrifice for Freedom®: World War II in the Pacific Student and Teacher Institute.

In June, all 16 student and teacher teams will meet in Oʻahu where they will walk in the footsteps of history, and learn firsthand about the impact of World War II in the Pacific.

Kate’s great grandfather was a prisoner of war and survived the Bataan Death March.

Learn about this incredible honor and remarkable story here:

https://www.starkvillesd.com/news/1672551/shs-student-and-teacher-team-selected-for-national-history-day-sacrifice-for-freedom-student-and-teacher-institute

post_text:
What an amazing opportunity for our students to experience living history! We were honored to welcome Holocaust survivor, Sami Steigmann, to AMS and SHS last week to share his story and a positive message about the power of dialogue.

“This is the first time MSU's Holmes Cultural Diversity Center has brought a speaker to Starkville public schools, said Rasheda Forbes, MSU assistant vice president for multicultural affairs. Steigmann is part of the last generation of Holocaust survivors, and hearing his story is "critically important" for middle and high school students to connect it to what they have learned in their history classes about WWII, she said.”
shared_text:

post_text:
‪SOSD 6th grader, Hannah, attended Overstreet Elementary while her father was deployed for 14 months. Because of her experience in Mrs. Mulrooney’s class during the time, Hannah & her mother wrote to Mississippi National Guard nominating Mrs. Mulrooney as Distinguished Teacher of the Year and Overstreet as School of the Year‬.

‪The awards were presented by Mississippi National Guard during this morning’s annual OES Veterans Program. SOSD is tremendously grateful for the sacrifices our deployed military families make and honored to be part of supporting them at school.‬

post_text:
What a moving Veterans Day Program at Overstreet Elementary! The OES Jacket Family welcomed veterans as our special guests with artwork and special presentations. Our own Chief Shumaker, US Army and Gulf War veteran, shared a powerful message: "We serve one race - the human race."

One of the sweetest and most special parts of the program was when students and faculty recognized their family members and friends for their service to our country.

post_text: Last week, SOSD students, Kobi and Ingrid, attended the White Cane Awareness event at Mississippi State University, along with some of their teachers. The event was designed to create awareness and celebrate the accomplishments of visually impaired students. Kobi and Ingrid had the opportunity to interact with a guide dog, play games and even try a white cane obstacle course highlighting the use of this mobility tool. Way to show off your #StarkvilleSpark, Kobi and Ingrid!

Reading has never been more fun! Sudduth, Henderson Ward Stewart, Overstreet and West Elementary Schools are participating in Mississippi Reads One Book, a unique opportunity for our students and families to read The World According to Humphrey - TOGETHER! Every student in grades pre-K-5th grades will receive a book to share with their family.

We kicked off this family literacy celebration with a book distribution at Sudduth today. The book project officially begins Monday, October 21.

#ExpectExcellence
